  <div class="abtit">Good feedback makes<br>better towns</div>
  <div class="ablead">
    Running a town is hard work. Keeping corridors clean, maintaining lifts, fighting pests, and a hundred more small things to juggle. As with anything complicated, it's hard to know what's working well and what needs more attention. Real problems can get missed even while town councils worry about the next complaint.
    <br><br>
    RateMyTown gives a clear view of how a town is serving its residents. It makes it easy for real residents to share their honest experience, while helping town councils get recognized for good work. Collective ratings show what to prioritize next, preventing real problems from being drowned out by loud complaints.
    <br><br>
    RateMyTown lets residents trust their most important problems will get looked at, and gives town councils the evidence they need to focus on their most important work.
  </div>

  <div class="abh">Principles</div>
  <div class="abrow">
    <div class="abnum">1</div>
    <div>
      <div class="abrt">Real residents, real experiences</div>
      <div class="abrd">Every rating comes from a verified resident of that town. One resident one review. No bots, no spammers, no astroturfing.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="abrow">
    <div class="abnum">2</div>
    <div>
      <div class="abrt">Honest anonymous feedback</div>
      <div class="abrd">Reviews are anonymous so you can share your real experience. We verify identity when you post, then forget who you are.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="abrow">
    <div class="abnum">3</div>
    <div>
      <div class="abrt">Sunlight, not flames</div>
      <div class="abrd">We're here to bring constructive visibility to problems, not tear each other down. Open information makes it clear what residents care about, brings recognition to good work, and helps us make better decisions.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="abquote">“The best towns are built when residents and councils can see the same honest picture and work from it together.”</div>

  <div class="abh">The thinking behind it</div>

  <div class="absub">If you make feedback hard, only angry people will give feedback</div>
  <div class="abprose">A town council exists to serve its residents well. Yet there is no good feedback loop for the experience of actual residents. Elections are too far apart and tangled with politics. Hotlines tackle acute issues, but don't record the day-to-day experience and lack visible accountability. <a href="https://www.mnd.gov.sg/our-work/regulating-town-councils/town-council-management-report-(tcmr)" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MND's Management Report</a> gives an auditor's view, but not the view of someone who actually lives there. When <a href="https://mothership.sg/2024/06/town-councils-tcmr-top-score/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">all towns score green on every indicator</a>, the report stops being useful. For something as important and complicated as daily life for <a href="https://www.hdb.gov.sg/-/media/doc/SCEG/HDB_Key-Statistics-2025.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">78% of Singapore residents</a>, the core feedback loop is broken.</div>
  <div class="abprose">Giving feedback nobody asked for takes effort, so it comes only from people who feel strongly. A broken loop means angry feedback. This makes councils want less of it, so the loop stays broken, and the feedback stays angry. Even in the best towns, satisfied residents get on with their lives rather than writing in. Town councils know this. <a href="https://maxwellpalmer.com/docs/articles/Einstein_Glick_Palmer_Participation.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">60% of American mayors say</a> housing decisions are shaped more by a small group with strong views than by majority opinion. But it's hard not to make decisions based on complaints when that's all you have.</div>
  <div class="abprose">Steering by complaints fails everyone. Town councils live in anxiety that the next call blows up on them. Residents' problems get missed unless they are willing to add to the noise. Meanwhile the quiet work that should be the focus of the job — service, maintenance, cleaning — gets that focus pulled away.</div>

  <div class="absub">Everything that gets better, gets better through feedback</div>
  <div class="abprose">For a town to do better, feedback needs to be easy. This surfaces views from all residents, not just those who are angry. Not all of it will be positive or useful, but it will be more moderate and representative. Town councils get better information on what the real problems are. Residents, meanwhile, have less frustration getting heard and more trust in what the town is doing.</div>
  <div class="abprose">Good feedback also protects against noisy complaints. When there are thousands of reviews praising a town's cleanliness, a lone complaint about a mess can be taken for what it is: a single incident. An unreasonable resident will still be heard, but against a track record of good service. Doctors spent years dreading review sites, until researchers found <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2917672/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">physician reviews were 88% positive</a>. Complaints don't stop, but they land in context. Easy, visible feedback is how the quiet work finally gets counted.</div>
  <div class="abprose">Most importantly, public feedback improves the services themselves. Hospitals that patients rate higher have <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22331980/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">lower death rates, and those they rate cleaner have lower infection rates</a>. In Uganda, villages that received <a href="https://www.povertyactionlab.org/evaluation/community-based-monitoring-primary-healthcare-providers-uganda" target="_blank" rel="noopener">public report cards on their local health clinics</a> saw clinic use go up and child mortality fall by a third. Feedback improves services <a href="https://accountabilityresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Fox-Social-Accountability-What-Does-the-Evidence-Really-Say-WDR-2015.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">when it is public and when someone can act on it</a>. Town councils fit both conditions. A rating about a dirty corridor doesn't have to travel through three ministries: the organization reading it is the one that schedules the cleaning.</div>

  <div class="absub">Credibility is critical</div>
  <div class="abprose">The key to making this all work is credibility. People need to trust that these are real, representative reviews. If reviews can be faked, there's no reason to trust the ratings. If only angry people show up, this just becomes another complaint forum. If people avoid giving their honest opinions out of fear, then the reviews become empty. Losing credibility means people stop paying attention, and the feedback loop breaks. Verification and critical mass are not features; they are the product.</div>
  <div class="abprose">The design follows from that. Every review comes from a Singpass-verified resident of the town. One review per person. No bots, no brigading, no spam. Reviews are also anonymous so people can be honest without worrying who's reading. We verify at the time of submission, then forget who you are. We solicit reviews rather than wait for whoever shows up — that's what keeps the sample representative. Everything is designed to maximize the credibility of the platform.</div>
  <div class="abprose">None of this guarantees success. What we are really testing is whether <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exit,_Voice,_and_Loyalty" target="_blank" rel="noopener">voice can be made to work where exit cannot</a>: an honest signal, from verified residents, in public view, read by an organization that can respond. RateMyTown is our attempt to put those pieces together — honest information, placed where it can actually do some good. The rest depends on residents willing to rate the good along with the bad, and town councils willing to read what they say.</div>

